2. Optimisation problem¶

In [8]:
G = loadmat("/Users/gladys/Documents/scolarite/Supelec/cours/cours 3A/Cours Mention/LSD/Parallelization through Majorization-Minimization approaches/TP sujet 3/data/G.mat")['G']

expression de f¶

$$ (\forall x \in \mathbb{R}^{N}) \ \ f(x) = \frac{1}{2} ||Hx-y||^{2} + \lambda \sum_{n=1}^{2N}{\psi([Gx]^{(n)})} $$

$H \in \mathbb{R}^{N N}$ : projection (discretization) matrix.
$\lambda$ : regularization parameter.
$\psi$ : potential function $\psi:u \in \mathbb{R} -> \sqrt{1+u^2/\delta^2} (>0)$.
$G \in \mathbb{R}^{2NN}$: sparse operator dedicated to contours enhancement.

Expression of the gradient $\nabla f$¶

Start from $\nabla f$ analytical expression obtained. $$ \forall x \ \ \ \nabla f(x) = H^{} (Hx y)+ \lambda G^{} ( \psi([Gx]^{n}))_{1\leq n \leq 2N}$$ \ Avec $\psi'(u)= \frac{1}{\delta^2} \frac{u}{\sqrt{1 + u^2 /\delta^2}}$
\ Denote $J_{l}$ the Jacobian matrix of $I$ and use the composition formula, to obtain : $$ \ \forall x \ \ \ \nabla^2f(x) = H^{}H+\lambda G^{}diag((\psi ([Gx]n))_{1n2N}) \ G$$ \ Avec $\psi''(u)= \frac{1}{\delta^2} \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{u^2}{\delta^2})^{3/2}}$

f est grad-Lipschitz¶

f is L-grad Lipschitz with $L=||H^{}H||+ \frac{\lambda}{\delta^2} ||G^{}G||$

3. Optimization algorithms¶

3.1 Gradient descent algorithm¶

$$x_0 \in \mathbb{R}^{N}, \\ \forall k\in\mathbb{N} \ \ \ x_{k+1} = x_k \frac{1}{L}\nabla f(x_k).$$
In [9]:

l = 0.13 #lambda

HTH = H.transpose() @ H
GTG = G.transpose() @ G

L = linalg.norm(HTH) + (l/delta**2) * linalg.norm(GTG)
print("Learning rate L = ", L)

In [10]:
# Definition of the psi and gradient functions 

def psi_prime(vect_u, l, delta):
    res = []
    for u in vect_u:
        res.append(1/delta**2 * u/math.sqrt(1 + u**2/delta**2))
    return np.array(res).reshape(-1, 1)

def gradient_f(x, y, l, delta):
    return H.transpose() @ (H@x - y) + l* (G.transpose() @ psi_prime(G@x, l, delta))
In [11]:
def solver(y, l, delta, L):
    x_previous = np.zeros((N,1)) #initialisation at 0
    x_n = x_previous + 0.99999/L * gradient_f(x_previous, y, l, delta)
    
    iter = 0
    while iter < 500: #np.linalg.norm(x_n - x_previous) > 10^(-3)
        x_previous = x_n
        x_n = x_previous - 0.99999/L * gradient_f(x_previous, y, l, delta)
        iter += 1
    
    return x_n

3.3 MM quadratic algorithm¶

MM Algorithm : $$x_{n+1} \in \underset{x \in H}{\arg\min}{ \ h(x,x_n)} \\ \text{where } h(,x_n) \text{ is a majorant function for } f \text{ at } x_n.$$

Quadratic majorant function¶

As $f$ is twice differentiable function on RN with Hessian $\nabla^2f$, the following $h$ function is a majorant of f at $x_0$:
\ $$\begin{align} (\forall x \in \mathbb{R}^N) h(x,x_0) &=f(x_0)+\nabla f(x_0)|xx_0+\frac{1}{2}xx_0|A(xx_0)\\ &=f(x_0)+\nabla f(x_0)^T(xx_0)+\frac{1}{2}(xx_0)^T A(x_0)(xx_0) \end{align} $$

where $A \in \mathbb{R}^{NN}$ a positive semidefinite matrix such that, for every $x \in \mathbb{R}^{N}$, $A \nabla^2f (x)$ is positive semidefinite.

$f(x) = g(x) + \lambda r(r)$ with $g(x) = \frac{1}{2} ||Hx-y||^{2}$ and $r(x) = \sum_{n=1}^{2N}{\psi([Gx]^{(n)})}$

For g: $$\begin{align} \forall (x,x0) g(x) &=g(x_0)+\nabla g(x_0)^(xx_0)+ \frac{1}{2}(xx_0)^ \nabla g^2(x_0) (xx_0),\\ &=g(x_0)+\nabla g(x_0)^(xx_0)+ \frac{1}{2}(xx_0)^ \boldsymbol{H^H} (xx_0) \end{align}$$

For r: $$r(x) \leq r(x_0)+\nabla r(x_0)^ (x x_0)+ \frac{1}{2}(x x_0)^ G^ \boldsymbol{diag \big( w ([Gx_0]^{(n)}) \big)} G(x x_0).$$ with $w(u) = \frac{\psi'(u)}{u} = \frac{1}{\delta^2} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 + u^2 /\delta^2}}$

By using the (positive) linear combination property of maj functions, the conclusion follows :

$$\forall x_0 \ \ A(x_0)=H^H+\lambda G^ diag\big(w([Gx_0]^{(n)}) \big) G \ \ \text{ is a good choice.}$$

Curvature A(x) of the majorant function¶

In [14]:
from scipy.sparse.linalg import LinearOperator
from scipy.sparse import diags

def b(vect_x0): #define b
    vect = G @ vect_x0
    res = []
    for u in vect:
        res.append(1/delta**2 * 1/math.sqrt(1 + u**2/delta**2))
    return np.array(res)#.reshape(-1, 1)

def mA(vect_x0):
    diag = diags(b(vect_x0)).tocsc()
    return HTH + l * (G.transpose() @ diag @ G) 

def A(x):
    return mA(x) #A(v) will return mv(v)

MM quadratic subspace algorithm¶

Problem : $$ x_{n+1} \in \underset{x}{\arg\min}{\ h(x, x_n)} $$ Algorithm : $$ \forall n \in \mathbb{N} \ \ \ x_{n+1} = x_n A(x_n)^{1}\nabla f (x_n)$$

In [15]:
from scipy.sparse.linalg import bicg


def solverMM(y, l, delta, L, max_iter):
    start = time.time()
    
    x_previous = np.zeros((N,1)) #initialisation at 0
    x_n = x_previous - bicg(A(x_previous), gradient_f(x_previous, y, l, delta))[0].reshape(N,1)
                            
    iter = 0
    while np.linalg.norm(x_n - x_previous) > 10^(-3) and iter < max_iter:
        x_previous = x_n
        x_n = x_previous - bicg(A(x_previous), gradient_f(x_previous, y, l, delta))[0].reshape(N,1)
        iter += 1
    
    end = time.time()
    return x_n, end - start

3.3 3MG algorithm (MM Memory Gradient)¶

Motivation : Most of the time (typically in ML) when N is too large, it becomes impossible to directly inverse the maj matrix $A(x_k)$ at each iteration ($O(N^3)$ operations). One possibility : Trick : Reduce the dimension by only searching the next iterate within given direction Acceleration of the MM quadratic algorithm using the Memory Gradient subspace.

Set of directions $D_n$ : $D_n = [-\nabla f(x_n) \ | \ d_{n-1}]$

$$ x_{n+1} \in \underset{x \in span(d_n^1,d_n^2,...,d_n^{M_n})}{\arg\min}{h(x, x_n)} $$
$$ (3MG)(\forall k \geq 1) \left\{ \begin{array}{11} u_k = argmin_{u \in \mathbb{R}^N} h(x_k+D_k u,x_k),\\ x_{k+1}=x_k+D_ku_k. \end{array} \right. $$

Memory gradient¶

$$x_0 \in \mathbb{R}^N \ \ \forall k \left\{ \begin{array}{11} D_k = [ \nabla f ( x_k ) \ , \ x_k x_{k-1} ] ,\\ u_k = \big(D_k^ A(x_k)D_k \big)^ D_k^T \ \nabla f(x_k), \\ x_{k + 1} = x_k + D_k u_k \end{array} \right.$$

with $x_{1} = 0$, $D_0 = \nabla f(x_0)$ and denotes the pseudo-inverse.

In [18]:
from scipy.linalg import pinv #for pseudo inverse

def solver3MG(y, l, delta, L, max_iter):
    start = time.time()
    
    #initialisation x0 = 0
    x_k = np.zeros((N,1)) 
    
    #initialisation D0 = - nabla f (x0)
    D_k = - gradient_f(x_k, y, l, delta) 
    
    # initialisation de u0
    HD_k = H@D_k
    GD_k = G@D_k
    D_kTnablaf = D_k.transpose() @ gradient_f(x_k, y, l, delta)
    u_k = - pinv(HD_k.transpose()@HD_k + l * (GD_k.transpose() @ diags(b(x_k)).tocsc() @ GD_k )) @ D_kTnablaf 
                            
    iter = 0
    while iter < max_iter:
        x_next = x_k + D_k @ u_k
        
        D_k = np.c_[-gradient_f(x_next, y, l, delta), (x_next - x_k)]
        
        x_k = x_next
        
        HD_k = H@D_k
        GD_k = G@D_k
        D_kTnablaf = D_k.transpose() @ gradient_f(x_k, y, l, delta)
        u_k = - pinv(HD_k.transpose()@HD_k + l * (GD_k.transpose()@ diags(b(x_k)).tocsc() @GD_k)) @ D_kTnablaf
        iter += 1
    
    end = time.time()
    
    return x_k, end - start

3.4 Block-coordinate MM quadratic algorithm¶

Instead of updating the whole coordinate of $x_k$, we only focus one precise group of them. The group turnover is made at each iteration according a cyclic rule. Denote by J the number of groups and then the j-th group is selected every $mod(k1,J)+1$ iterations.

$$\text{(BC-MM)} \ \ x \in \mathbb{R}^N \ \ \forall k \left\{ \begin{array}{11} j = mod(k1,J)+1,\\ \mathcal{G}_j = \big\{ N_j(j1)+1,...,jN_j\big\}\\ x_{k+1}[\mathcal{G}_j] = x_k[\mathcal{G}_j] A_j(x_k)^{1}\nabla f(x_k)[\mathcal{G}_j] \end{array} \right. $$

where

  • $A_j = H_j^H_j + \lambda \ \ G_j^diag\big(w([Gx_k]^{(n)}) \big) G_j \in \mathbb{R}^{N_jN_j}$
  • $H_j =H[: \ ,\mathcal{G}_j] \in \mathbb{R}^{2NN_j}, G_j =G[: \ ,\mathcal{G}_j] \mathbb{R}^{2NN_j}$
  • $N_j = N/K$ (with various K) this means $J = N/N_j = K.$

We will be testing this algorithm for $K \in \{1,2,3,5,6,9\}$

In [24]:
def solverBlockMM(y, l, delta, L, max_iter, K):
    start = time.time()
    
    Nj = int(N/K)
    #initialisation x0 = 0
    x_next = np.zeros((N,1))            
    iter = 1
    while iter < max_iter:
        x_k = x_next
        
        j = (iter-1)%K + 1
        
        g = range(Nj*(j-1), j*Nj, 1)
        
        Hj = H[:,g]
        Gj = G[:,g]
        diag = diags(b(x_k)).tocsc()
        Aj = Hj.transpose() @ Hj + l * Gj.transpose() @ diag @ Gj
        
        x_next = x_k
        x_next[g] = x_k[g] - bicg(Aj, gradient_f(x_k, y, l, delta)[g])[0].reshape(Nj,1)
        
        iter += 1
    
    end = time.time()
    
    return x_next, end - start

3.5 Parallel MM quadratic algorithm¶

The principle of parallel MM is to replace the majorant matrix A by an other one B that is a diagonal majorant matrix, in order to promote a parallel implementation.

$$\text{(Parallel MM)} \ \ x \in \mathbb{R}^N \ \ \forall k \left\{ \begin{array}{11} x_0 \in \mathbb{R}^{N} \\ \forall k \in \mathbb{N} x_{k+1} = x_k B(x_k)^{1}\nabla f(x_k) \end{array} \right.$$

with

  • $\forall k B(x_k)=diag\big(b^{(i)}(x_k)\big)$.
  • $\mathcal{H}_i^{(m)} = |H^{(m,i)}|\sum_{p=1}^{N}|H^{(m,p)}|$ and $\mathcal{G}_i^{(m)} = |G^{(m,i)}|\sum_{p=1}{N}|G^{(m,p)}|$
  • $b^{(i)}(x) = \mathcal{H}^ \boldsymbol{1} + \lambda \mathcal{G}^ \big( w[[Gx]]{(n)}))_{1 \leq n \leq 2N}$
In [ ]:
